body:
Vitest's `vi.mock()` calls are hoisted to the top of the file, before any `import` or `const` statements. This means you can't reference variables declared in the test file inside `vi.mock()`.

```typescript
// BAD: mockFn is undefined because vi.mock is hoisted above this line
const mockFn = vi.fn();
vi.mock('./api', () => ({
  fetchUser: mockFn, // undefined at hoist time!
}));

// GOOD: use vi.hoisted() to declare mocks that survive hoisting
const { mockFetch } = vi.hoisted(() => ({
  mockFetch: vi.fn(),
}));
vi.mock('./api', () => ({
  fetchUser: mockFetch, // works!
}));

// ALSO GOOD: define mocks inline
vi.mock('./api', () => ({
  fetchUser: vi.fn().mockResolvedValue({ id: 1, name: 'Alice' }),
}));
```

`vi.hoisted()` was introduced specifically to solve this problem. It returns values that are available at hoist time. This is the same issue Jest has with `jest.mock()` hoisting.

By default, Jest mocks persist between tests in the same file. If one test modifies a mock's implementation, subsequent tests see the modified version.

```typescript
// BAD: mock state leaks between tests
import { fetchData } from './api';
jest.mock('./api');
const mockFetchData = fetchData as jest.MockedFunction<typeof fetchData>;

test('handles success', () => {
  mockFetchData.mockResolvedValue({ data: 'ok' });
  // ...
});

test('handles error', () => {
  // mockFetchData still has the success implementation!
  mockFetchData.mockRejectedValue(new Error('fail'));
});

// GOOD: reset in beforeEach
beforeEach(() => {
  jest.resetAllMocks();  // resets implementation AND call history
  // or: jest.clearAllMocks()  // resets call history only
  // or: jest.restoreAllMocks()  // restores original implementation
});

// Or configure globally in jest.config.ts
export default {
  clearMocks: true,      // auto-clear before each test
  restoreMocks: true,    // auto-restore before each test
};
```

The difference: `clearMocks` clears call history but keeps implementation. `resetMocks` also removes implementations. `restoreMocks` restores original functions (for spyOn).

Unlike Jest which runs each test file in a separate worker, Vitest runs tests in threads with shared module state by default. This can cause flaky tests when files share global state.

```typescript
// vitest.config.ts
import { defineConfig } from 'vitest/config';

export default defineConfig({
  test: {
    // Option 1: Use separate worker threads (like Jest)
    pool: 'forks',

    // Option 2: Run specific files sequentially
    sequence: {
      concurrent: false, // tests within a file run sequentially
    },

    // Option 3: isolate tests (restart worker between files)
    isolate: true,

    // Option 4: Force specific files to run alone
    // In the test file:
    // // @vitest-environment node
  },
});
```

```typescript
// Force a specific test file to run sequentially
// test/database.test.ts
import { describe, it, beforeAll, afterAll } from 'vitest';

// This file needs sequential execution
describe.sequential('Database tests', () => {
  it('creates a record', () => { /* ... */ });
  it('reads the record', () => { /* ... */ });
});
```

If tests pass individually but fail together, suspect shared state. The `pool: 'forks'` option gives full isolation at the cost of startup speed.

When using `jest.useFakeTimers()`, advancing timers doesn't automatically flush the microtask queue. Promises may not resolve even after advancing time.

```typescript
// BAD: promise never resolves
jest.useFakeTimers();

test('delayed fetch', async () => {
  const promise = fetchWithRetry(); // uses setTimeout internally
  jest.advanceTimersByTime(5000);
  const result = await promise; // hangs!
});

// GOOD: flush promises between timer advances
jest.useFakeTimers();

test('delayed fetch', async () => {
  const promise = fetchWithRetry();

  // Advance timers and flush microtask queue
  jest.advanceTimersByTime(1000);
  await Promise.resolve(); // flush microtask queue

  jest.advanceTimersByTime(2000);
  await Promise.resolve();

  const result = await promise;
  expect(result).toBeDefined();
});

// BEST: use jest.advanceTimersByTimeAsync (Jest 29.5+)
test('delayed fetch', async () => {
  const promise = fetchWithRetry();
  await jest.advanceTimersByTimeAsync(5000); // advances timers AND flushes promises
  const result = await promise;
  expect(result).toBeDefined();
});
```

`jest.advanceTimersByTimeAsync` is the clean solution — it interleaves timer advancement and promise flushing. Use it whenever testing async code with timers.

Vitest uses `.snap` files in `__snapshots__/` directories like Jest, but the internal format differs slightly. Migrating from Jest requires re-generating all snapshots.

```bash
# Regenerate all snapshots after migrating from Jest to Vitest
npx vitest run --update

# Or update specific test file's snapshots
npx vitest run --update src/components/Button.test.tsx
```

```typescript
// Inline snapshots work the same
test('renders correctly', () => {
  const result = render(<Button label="Click" />);
  expect(result).toMatchInlineSnapshot(`
    <button class="btn">
      Click
    </button>
  `);
});

// File snapshots
test('complex output', () => {
  expect(generateReport()).toMatchSnapshot();
  // Creates: __snapshots__/report.test.ts.snap
});

// Named snapshots for clarity
test('multiple states', () => {
  expect(render(<Btn disabled />)).toMatchSnapshot('disabled state');
  expect(render(<Btn loading />)).toMatchSnapshot('loading state');
});
```

Snapshot testing tip: review snapshot diffs carefully in PRs. Large snapshots become rubber-stamp approvals. Keep snapshots small and focused on the important output.

Spying on default exports requires importing the module object, not the default export directly.

```typescript
// utils.ts
export default function calculateTotal(items: number[]): number {
  return items.reduce((sum, item) => sum + item, 0);
}

// BAD: can't spy on default import directly
import calculateTotal from './utils';
vi.spyOn(???, 'calculateTotal'); // what object?

// GOOD: import as module object
import * as utils from './utils';
vi.spyOn(utils, 'default').mockReturnValue(100);

// Or better: mock the whole module
vi.mock('./utils', () => ({
  default: vi.fn().mockReturnValue(100),
}));

// BEST: prefer named exports over default exports for testability
// utils.ts
export function calculateTotal(items: number[]): number {
  return items.reduce((sum, item) => sum + item, 0);
}

// Now spying is straightforward
import * as utils from './utils';
vi.spyOn(utils, 'calculateTotal').mockReturnValue(100);
```

Named exports are inherently easier to mock and spy on. If you control the code, prefer named exports over default exports for better testability.

When you mock a module in Jest with TypeScript, the imported functions are still typed as their original types, not as `jest.Mock`. You must cast them to access mock methods.

```typescript
import { fetchUser } from './api';
jest.mock('./api');

// BAD: TypeScript error — fetchUser.mockResolvedValue is not a function
fetchUser.mockResolvedValue({ id: 1 }); // TS error

// GOOD: cast to jest.MockedFunction
const mockFetchUser = fetchUser as jest.MockedFunction<typeof fetchUser>;
mockFetchUser.mockResolvedValue({ id: 1, name: 'Alice' });

// GOOD: use jest.mocked() helper (Jest 27.4+)
const mockFetchUser = jest.mocked(fetchUser);
mockFetchUser.mockResolvedValue({ id: 1, name: 'Alice' });

// Mock entire module with type safety
jest.mock('./api');
const mockApi = jest.mocked(await import('./api'));
mockApi.fetchUser.mockResolvedValue({ id: 1, name: 'Alice' });
mockApi.updateUser.mockResolvedValue(true);
```

`jest.mocked()` provides deep mocking types. Use it instead of manual casting for cleaner code. In Vitest, the equivalent is `vi.mocked()`.

Vitest doesn't include a coverage provider by default. You must install one, and the configuration varies between providers.

```bash
# Install coverage provider
npm install -D @vitest/coverage-v8
# or
npm install -D @vitest/coverage-istanbul
```

```typescript
// vitest.config.ts
import { defineConfig } from 'vitest/config';

export default defineConfig({
  test: {
    coverage: {
      provider: 'v8', // or 'istanbul'
      reporter: ['text', 'json', 'html', 'lcov'],
      reportsDirectory: './coverage',
      include: ['src/**/*.{ts,tsx}'],
      exclude: [
        'src/**/*.test.{ts,tsx}',
        'src/**/*.d.ts',
        'src/types/**',
        'src/**/index.ts', // barrel files
      ],
      thresholds: {
        lines: 80,
        functions: 80,
        branches: 70,
        statements: 80,
      },
    },
  },
});
```

```bash
# Run with coverage
npx vitest run --coverage

# Watch mode with coverage
npx vitest --coverage
```

V8 provider is faster but less accurate for some edge cases (branches). Istanbul is slower but more battle-tested. For CI, use `lcov` reporter for integration with Codecov/Coveralls.

Jest's `moduleNameMapper` uses regular expressions for path matching, not glob patterns. Using globs silently fails — imports just won't be mapped.

```typescript
// jest.config.ts
export default {
  // BAD: glob pattern doesn't work
  moduleNameMapper: {
    '@/components/*': '<rootDir>/src/components/*',  // won't work!
  },

  // GOOD: regex pattern with capture group
  moduleNameMapper: {
    '^@/(.*)$': '<rootDir>/src/$1',
    '^@components/(.*)$': '<rootDir>/src/components/$1',
    // Mock CSS/assets
    '\\.(css|less|scss)$': 'identity-obj-proxy',
    '\\.(jpg|jpeg|png|svg)$': '<rootDir>/test/__mocks__/fileMock.ts',
  },
};
```

```typescript
// test/__mocks__/fileMock.ts
export default 'test-file-stub';
```

The `^` anchor and `(.*)$` capture group are essential. Without `^`, the pattern matches anywhere in the module path. Without the capture group `$1`, the resolved path is wrong.

When using `test.each` with a template literal or array of arrays, TypeScript may infer the parameters as `any` unless you provide type hints.

```typescript
// BAD: parameters typed as any
test.each([
  [1, 2, 3],
  [2, 3, 5],
])('adds %i + %i = %i', (a, b, expected) => {
  // a, b, expected are all 'any'
  expect(add(a, b)).toBe(expected);
});

// GOOD: use typed array
test.each<[number, number, number]>([
  [1, 2, 3],
  [2, 3, 5],
])('adds %i + %i = %i', (a, b, expected) => {
  // a, b, expected are number
  expect(add(a, b)).toBe(expected);
});

// BEST: use object syntax for clarity
test.each([
  { a: 1, b: 2, expected: 3 },
  { a: 2, b: 3, expected: 5 },
  { a: -1, b: 1, expected: 0 },
])('adds $a + $b = $expected', ({ a, b, expected }) => {
  expect(add(a, b)).toBe(expected);
});

// Object syntax with describe.each
describe.each([
  { name: 'Chrome', ua: 'Mozilla/5.0 Chrome' },
  { name: 'Firefox', ua: 'Mozilla/5.0 Firefox' },
])('$name browser', ({ ua }) => {
  test('parses user agent', () => {
    expect(parseUA(ua)).toBeDefined();
  });
});
```

MSW (Mock Service Worker) interceptors match against the full URL. If your app prepends a base URL, the handler must include it or use a wildcard.

```typescript
import { http, HttpResponse } from 'msw';
import { setupServer } from 'msw/node';

// BAD: won't match if your app calls https://api.example.com/users
const handlers = [
  http.get('/users', () => HttpResponse.json([{ id: 1 }])),
];

// GOOD: match exact URL
const handlers = [
  http.get('https://api.example.com/users', () => {
    return HttpResponse.json([{ id: 1, name: 'Alice' }]);
  }),
];

// GOOD: use wildcard for any base URL
const handlers = [
  http.get('*/users', () => {
    return HttpResponse.json([{ id: 1, name: 'Alice' }]);
  }),
];

// GOOD: use path parameters
const handlers = [
  http.get('*/users/:id', ({ params }) => {
    return HttpResponse.json({ id: params.id, name: 'Alice' });
  }),
];

const server = setupServer(...handlers);

beforeAll(() => server.listen({ onUnhandledRequest: 'error' }));
afterEach(() => server.resetHandlers());
afterAll(() => server.close());
```

Setting `onUnhandledRequest: 'error'` makes tests fail on any unhandled API call, which catches missing handlers early.

If an async test throws after the test function returns, Jest marks it as passed. The error appears as an unhandled rejection warning, not a test failure.

```typescript
// BAD: test passes even if fetchUser rejects!
test('fetches user', () => {
  fetchUser(1).then(user => {
    expect(user.name).toBe('Alice');
  });
  // test returns before promise resolves
});

// BAD: missing await
test('fetches user', async () => {
  const promise = fetchUser(1);
  // forgot await — test ends before assertion runs
  expect(promise).resolves.toHaveProperty('name', 'Alice');
});

// GOOD: always await async operations
test('fetches user', async () => {
  const user = await fetchUser(1);
  expect(user.name).toBe('Alice');
});

// GOOD: return the promise
test('fetches user', () => {
  return fetchUser(1).then(user => {
    expect(user.name).toBe('Alice');
  });
});

// GOOD: use resolves/rejects with await
test('fetches user', async () => {
  await expect(fetchUser(1)).resolves.toHaveProperty('name', 'Alice');
  await expect(fetchUser(999)).rejects.toThrow('Not found');
});
```

Lint rule: enable `jest/no-done-callback` and `jest/valid-expect-in-promise` to catch these issues at lint time.

Testing React components with Vitest's browser mode uses real browser APIs, not jsdom. The setup is different from the default Node-based test environment.

```typescript
// vitest.config.ts for browser testing
import { defineConfig } from 'vitest/config';

export default defineConfig({
  test: {
    // For component tests with jsdom (faster, no real browser)
    environment: 'jsdom',
    setupFiles: ['./test/setup.ts'],

    // OR for real browser testing
    browser: {
      enabled: true,
      name: 'chromium',
      provider: 'playwright',
    },
  },
});
```

```typescript
// test/setup.ts — for jsdom environment
import '@testing-library/jest-dom/vitest';
import { cleanup } from '@testing-library/react';
import { afterEach } from 'vitest';

afterEach(() => {
  cleanup(); // unmount React components
});
```

Jsdom is fine for most component tests and is much faster than browser mode. Use browser mode only when you need real browser APIs (Canvas, WebGL, Web Workers, real CSS layout calculations).

Jest uses CommonJS by default and doesn't transform `node_modules`. ESM-only packages throw `SyntaxError: Cannot use import statement outside a module`.

```typescript
// Error: SyntaxError: Cannot use import statement outside a module
// Caused by: an ESM-only dependency in node_modules/

// jest.config.ts — allow specific packages to be transformed
export default {
  transformIgnorePatterns: [
    // Transform specific ESM packages
    'node_modules/(?!(uuid|nanoid|@tanstack/react-query|msw)/)',
  ],
  // Or use a blanket ESM transform (slower)
  // transformIgnorePatterns: ['/node_modules/(?!.+\\.mjs$)/'],

  // If using ts-jest:
  transform: {
    '^.+\\.tsx?$': 'ts-jest',
    '^.+\\.mjs$': 'ts-jest', // handle .mjs files
  },
};
```

Alternative: switch to Vitest, which handles ESM natively. If you must stay on Jest, `jest-environment-jsdom` version 29+ supports ESM better. Or use `jest --experimental-vm-modules` flag for native ESM support.

You can't call hooks directly in tests because they must run inside a React component. Use `renderHook` from `@testing-library/react`.

```typescript
// BAD: hooks can only be called inside a component
test('useCounter', () => {
  const { count, increment } = useCounter(); // Error!
});

// GOOD: use renderHook
import { renderHook, act } from '@testing-library/react';
import { useCounter } from './useCounter';

test('useCounter increments', () => {
  const { result } = renderHook(() => useCounter());

  expect(result.current.count).toBe(0);

  act(() => {
    result.current.increment();
  });

  expect(result.current.count).toBe(1);
});

// With initial props
test('useCounter with initial value', () => {
  const { result, rerender } = renderHook(
    ({ initial }) => useCounter(initial),
    { initialProps: { initial: 10 } }
  );

  expect(result.current.count).toBe(10);

  // Test with different props
  rerender({ initial: 20 });
  expect(result.current.count).toBe(20);
});

// Hook with context provider
test('useAuth with provider', () => {
  const wrapper = ({ children }) => (
    <AuthProvider>{children}</AuthProvider>
  );
  const { result } = renderHook(() => useAuth(), { wrapper });
  expect(result.current.user).toBeNull();
});
```

When mocking functions with complex signatures, `vi.fn()` infers `Mock<any>` unless you provide the function type explicitly.

```typescript
type UserService = {
  getUser: (id: number) => Promise<{ id: number; name: string }>;
  updateUser: (id: number, data: Partial<User>) => Promise<User>;
};

// BAD: loses type information
const mockGetUser = vi.fn(); // vi.Mock<any>
mockGetUser(1); // no autocomplete, no type checking

// GOOD: provide the type
const mockGetUser = vi.fn<(id: number) => Promise<{ id: number; name: string }>>();
mockGetUser.mockResolvedValue({ id: 1, name: 'Alice' }); // type-checked
mockGetUser.mockResolvedValue({ id: 'wrong' }); // TypeScript error!

// GOOD: use satisfies for object mocks
const mockService: UserService = {
  getUser: vi.fn().mockResolvedValue({ id: 1, name: 'Alice' }),
  updateUser: vi.fn().mockResolvedValue({ id: 1, name: 'Bob' }),
};

// GOOD: use vi.mocked for imported functions
import { getUser } from './api';
vi.mock('./api');
const mocked = vi.mocked(getUser);
mocked.mockResolvedValue({ id: 1, name: 'Alice' }); // fully typed
```

`toHaveBeenCalledWith` checks exact argument equality using `expect().toEqual()` internally. Partial objects or extra properties cause test failures.

```typescript
const mockFn = jest.fn();
mockFn({ id: 1, name: 'Alice', role: 'admin', createdAt: new Date() });

// FAILS: doesn't match all properties
expect(mockFn).toHaveBeenCalledWith({ id: 1, name: 'Alice' });

// GOOD: use expect.objectContaining for partial matching
expect(mockFn).toHaveBeenCalledWith(
  expect.objectContaining({ id: 1, name: 'Alice' })
);

// Combine with other matchers
expect(mockFn).toHaveBeenCalledWith(
  expect.objectContaining({
    id: expect.any(Number),
    name: expect.stringContaining('Ali'),
    role: expect.stringMatching(/admin|editor/),
    createdAt: expect.any(Date),
  })
);

// For arrays:
expect(mockFn).toHaveBeenCalledWith(
  expect.arrayContaining([1, 2])
);

// Ignore specific arguments:
expect(mockFn).toHaveBeenCalledWith(
  'first-arg',
  expect.anything(), // any value
  'third-arg'
);
```

`expect.objectContaining` is the most-used asymmetric matcher. It works in both Jest and Vitest. Combine matchers for powerful, flexible assertions.

Unlike Jest where `describe`, `test`, `expect` are automatically global, Vitest requires explicit imports or a configuration flag.

```typescript
// Without globals: must import everything
import { describe, it, expect, vi, beforeEach, afterEach } from 'vitest';

describe('MyTest', () => {
  it('works', () => {
    expect(true).toBe(true);
  });
});

// With globals: works like Jest
// vitest.config.ts
export default defineConfig({
  test: {
    globals: true, // enable global test APIs
  },
});

// tsconfig.json — add types for global autocomplete
{
  "compilerOptions": {
    "types": ["vitest/globals"]
  }
}

// Now you can use without imports:
describe('MyTest', () => {
  it('works', () => {
    expect(true).toBe(true);
  });
});
```

Explicit imports are actually preferred in large codebases — they make dependencies clear and allow tree-shaking. But `globals: true` makes migration from Jest easier.

React state updates triggered by user interactions must be wrapped in `act()` or use Testing Library's built-in event methods which handle this automatically.

```typescript
import { render, screen, fireEvent } from '@testing-library/react';
import userEvent from '@testing-library/user-event';

// BAD: direct state mutation without act
test('counter', () => {
  const { container } = render(<Counter />);
  container.querySelector('button')?.click(); // warning: not wrapped in act()
});

// GOOD: use fireEvent (auto-wrapped in act)
test('counter increments', () => {
  render(<Counter />);
  fireEvent.click(screen.getByRole('button', { name: 'Increment' }));
  expect(screen.getByText('Count: 1')).toBeInTheDocument();
});

// BEST: use userEvent for realistic interactions
test('counter increments', async () => {
  const user = userEvent.setup();
  render(<Counter />);

  await user.click(screen.getByRole('button', { name: 'Increment' }));
  expect(screen.getByText('Count: 1')).toBeInTheDocument();

  // userEvent simulates real browser behavior:
  await user.type(screen.getByRole('textbox'), 'Hello');
  await user.keyboard('{Enter}');
  await user.hover(screen.getByText('Tooltip trigger'));
});
```

`userEvent` is preferred over `fireEvent` because it simulates actual browser event sequences (mousedown, mouseup, click, etc.), catching more real-world bugs.

Without `expect.assertions()`, a test that should throw might pass silently if the code doesn't actually throw, because the `catch` block (with its assertions) is never reached.

```typescript
// BAD: passes even if validateEmail doesn't throw
test('rejects invalid email', async () => {
  try {
    await validateEmail('not-an-email');
  } catch (e) {
    expect(e.message).toBe('Invalid email');
  }
  // If validateEmail doesn't throw, test passes with 0 assertions!
});

// GOOD: expect.assertions guarantees assertions ran
test('rejects invalid email', async () => {
  expect.assertions(1); // exactly 1 assertion must run
  try {
    await validateEmail('not-an-email');
  } catch (e) {
    expect(e.message).toBe('Invalid email');
  }
});

// BETTER: use rejects matcher
test('rejects invalid email', async () => {
  await expect(validateEmail('not-an-email')).rejects.toThrow('Invalid email');
});

// For sync throws:
test('throws on null input', () => {
  expect(() => processData(null)).toThrow('Input required');
});
```

The `.rejects.toThrow()` pattern is the cleanest. Use `expect.assertions(n)` when the control flow is complex and you want to guarantee all assertions ran.

When a module uses dynamic `import()`, `vi.mock()` may not intercept it because the dynamic import bypasses the hoisted mock setup.

```typescript
// module.ts
export async function loadPlugin(name: string) {
  const plugin = await import(`./plugins/${name}`);
  return plugin.default;
}

// BAD: vi.mock won't catch dynamic imports with template literals
vi.mock('./plugins/auth', () => ({
  default: { name: 'mock-auth' },
}));

// GOOD: use vi.mock with the exact path
vi.mock('./plugins/auth', () => ({
  default: { name: 'mock-auth' },
}));
// And ensure the dynamic import resolves to the same path

// BETTER: mock the import function itself
const mockPlugin = { name: 'mock-plugin', init: vi.fn() };
vi.stubGlobal('import', vi.fn().mockResolvedValue({ default: mockPlugin }));

// BEST: restructure code to be more testable
// Instead of dynamic import, use dependency injection:
export function createLoader(plugins: Record<string, Plugin>) {
  return (name: string) => plugins[name];
}

// Test:
const loader = createLoader({ auth: mockPlugin });
expect(loader('auth')).toBe(mockPlugin);
```

Dynamic imports are inherently harder to test. When possible, restructure the code to accept dependencies as parameters.

The distinction between `setupFiles` and `setupFilesAfterFramework` matters for when globals like `expect` are available.

```typescript
// jest.config.ts
export default {
  // Runs BEFORE Jest globals (describe, expect) are available
  setupFiles: ['./test/env-setup.ts'],

  // Runs AFTER Jest globals are available
  setupFilesAfterFramework: ['./test/test-setup.ts'],
};

// test/env-setup.ts — for environment configuration
process.env.NODE_ENV = 'test';
process.env.DATABASE_URL = 'postgresql://localhost:5432/testdb';
// Can NOT use expect(), describe(), etc. here

// test/test-setup.ts — for test framework extensions
import '@testing-library/jest-dom';
import { server } from './mocks/server';

// CAN use expect(), beforeAll(), etc. here
beforeAll(() => server.listen());
afterEach(() => server.resetHandlers());
afterAll(() => server.close());

// Custom matcher
expect.extend({
  toBeWithinRange(received, floor, ceiling) {
    const pass = received >= floor && received <= ceiling;
    return { pass, message: () => `expected ${received} to be within [${floor}, ${ceiling}]` };
  },
});
```

In Vitest, the equivalent is `setupFiles` (all run after Vitest globals are available), so this distinction doesn't exist.

Instead of configuring a single test environment globally, you can set the environment per test file using a special comment at the top.

```typescript
// @vitest-environment jsdom
import { render, screen } from '@testing-library/react';

test('renders button', () => {
  render(<button>Click</button>);
  expect(screen.getByRole('button')).toBeInTheDocument();
});
```

```typescript
// @vitest-environment node
import { readFile } from 'fs/promises';

test('reads file', async () => {
  const content = await readFile('./test/fixtures/data.json', 'utf-8');
  expect(JSON.parse(content)).toHaveProperty('version');
});
```

```typescript
// Or configure per-file patterns in vitest.config.ts
export default defineConfig({
  test: {
    environment: 'node', // default
    environmentMatchGlobs: [
      ['src/components/**/*.test.tsx', 'jsdom'],
      ['src/api/**/*.test.ts', 'node'],
      ['src/workers/**/*.test.ts', 'edge-runtime'],
    ],
  },
});
```

This is useful in monorepos or full-stack apps where you have both DOM-dependent component tests and Node-only backend tests in the same project.

MSW 2.0 introduced breaking changes to the handler API. V1 patterns don't work in v2 and vice versa.

```typescript
// MSW v1 (OLD — don't use)
import { rest } from 'msw';
const handlers = [
  rest.get('/api/users', (req, res, ctx) => {
    return res(ctx.status(200), ctx.json([{ id: 1 }]));
  }),
];

// MSW v2 (CURRENT)
import { http, HttpResponse } from 'msw';
const handlers = [
  http.get('/api/users', () => {
    return HttpResponse.json([{ id: 1, name: 'Alice' }]);
  }),

  http.post('/api/users', async ({ request }) => {
    const body = await request.json();
    return HttpResponse.json({ id: 2, ...body }, { status: 201 });
  }),

  // Error response
  http.get('/api/error', () => {
    return HttpResponse.json(
      { message: 'Not found' },
      { status: 404 }
    );
  }),

  // Network error
  http.get('/api/network-error', () => {
    return HttpResponse.error();
  }),
];
```

Key v2 changes: `rest` renamed to `http`, response is returned directly (no `res/ctx`), request body is accessed via `request.json()`, `HttpResponse` replaces the response composition API.

`toEqual` considers `{ a: 1, b: undefined }` and `{ a: 1 }` as different because one has an explicit `undefined` property. This trips people up when testing API responses.

```typescript
// These are NOT equal with toEqual
expect({ a: 1, b: undefined }).toEqual({ a: 1 });
// FAILS: { a: 1, b: undefined } !== { a: 1 }

// These ARE equal with toEqual
expect({ a: 1, b: undefined }).toEqual({ a: 1, b: undefined });
// PASSES

// Use toMatchObject for partial matching (ignores extra properties)
expect({ a: 1, b: undefined, c: 3 }).toMatchObject({ a: 1 });
// PASSES — only checks specified properties

// Use toStrictEqual to also check for undefined properties (strictest)
expect({ a: 1 }).toStrictEqual({ a: 1 }); // PASSES
expect({ a: 1, b: undefined }).toStrictEqual({ a: 1 }); // FAILS

// Practical example:
const result = await api.getUser(1);
// If API sometimes includes optional fields as undefined:
expect(result).toMatchObject({
  id: 1,
  name: expect.any(String),
});
// toMatchObject is the safest choice for partial assertions
```

Without strict TypeScript configuration, `mockResolvedValue` accepts any value even if it doesn't match the mocked function's return type.

```typescript
import { vi, expect, test } from 'vitest';

type User = { id: number; name: string; email: string };
const getUser = vi.fn<(id: number) => Promise<User>>();

// With strict TS: type error (missing email)
getUser.mockResolvedValue({ id: 1, name: 'Alice' }); // TS error!

// Without strict TS: silently passes, tests may give false confidence
getUser.mockResolvedValue({ id: 1, name: 'Alice' } as any); // no error

// GOOD: use satisfies for compile-time validation
const mockUser = {
  id: 1,
  name: 'Alice',
  email: 'alice@test.com',
} satisfies User;
getUser.mockResolvedValue(mockUser);

// BEST: create test fixtures with type safety
function createMockUser(overrides: Partial<User> = {}): User {
  return {
    id: 1,
    name: 'Test User',
    email: 'test@test.com',
    ...overrides,
  };
}
getUser.mockResolvedValue(createMockUser({ name: 'Alice' }));
```

Factory functions for test data are the gold standard. They ensure type safety, reduce duplication, and make tests easier to read.

Testing Library's queries are ranked by how closely they match user behavior. Using the wrong query hides accessibility issues in your components.

```typescript
// Priority order (most preferred → least preferred):

// 1. getByRole — best, tests accessibility
screen.getByRole('button', { name: 'Submit' });
screen.getByRole('heading', { level: 1 });
screen.getByRole('textbox', { name: 'Email' });

// 2. getByLabelText — for form fields
screen.getByLabelText('Email address');

// 3. getByPlaceholderText — fallback for unlabeled inputs
screen.getByPlaceholderText('Enter email');

// 4. getByText — for non-interactive elements
screen.getByText('Welcome back');
screen.getByText(/welcome/i); // case-insensitive regex

// 5. getByDisplayValue — for filled form elements
screen.getByDisplayValue('alice@test.com');

// 6. getByAltText — for images
screen.getByAltText('User avatar');

// 7. getByTitle — rarely used
screen.getByTitle('Close');

// 8. getByTestId — LAST RESORT
screen.getByTestId('custom-element');
// If you need getByTestId, your component likely has accessibility issues
```

If you can't find an element with `getByRole`, it probably means your component is missing ARIA attributes. Fix the component, don't reach for `getByTestId`.

Vitest uses Vite's resolve config. If your app uses path aliases (like `@/`), you must configure them in `vitest.config.ts`, not just `tsconfig.json`.

```typescript
// Error: Failed to resolve import "@/utils/auth" from "src/tests/auth.test.ts"

// vitest.config.ts — add resolve aliases
import { defineConfig } from 'vitest/config';
import path from 'path';

export default defineConfig({
  resolve: {
    alias: {
      '@': path.resolve(__dirname, './src'),
      '@components': path.resolve(__dirname, './src/components'),
      '@utils': path.resolve(__dirname, './src/utils'),
    },
  },
  test: {
    globals: true,
    environment: 'jsdom',
  },
});

// Or if using vite.config.ts already, extend it:
import { defineConfig, mergeConfig } from 'vitest/config';
import viteConfig from './vite.config';

export default mergeConfig(
  viteConfig,
  defineConfig({
    test: {
      globals: true,
    },
  })
);
```

If you use `vite-tsconfig-paths` plugin in your Vite config, it automatically resolves TypeScript path aliases in tests too.

This means your test is running in the Node environment but trying to access DOM APIs. You need to set the test environment to `jsdom`.

```typescript
// jest.config.ts
export default {
  // Global setting
  testEnvironment: 'jsdom',

  // Or per-project in monorepo
  projects: [
    {
      displayName: 'components',
      testMatch: ['<rootDir>/src/components/**/*.test.tsx'],
      testEnvironment: 'jsdom',
    },
    {
      displayName: 'api',
      testMatch: ['<rootDir>/src/api/**/*.test.ts'],
      testEnvironment: 'node',
    },
  ],
};
```

```typescript
// Or per-file with docblock
/**
 * @jest-environment jsdom
 */
import { render, screen } from '@testing-library/react';

test('renders component', () => {
  render(<Button />);
  expect(screen.getByRole('button')).toBeInTheDocument();
});
```

Install `jest-environment-jsdom` separately since Jest 27: `npm install -D jest-environment-jsdom`. It's no longer bundled with Jest.

This error occurs when `vi.mock()` is called after the module has been imported and used. Mock hoisting isn't working, usually due to incorrect setup.

```typescript
// BAD: import executes before vi.mock due to circular dependency or bundler issue
import { fetchUser } from './api';
// ... some code that calls fetchUser ...
vi.mock('./api'); // too late! Module already loaded

// GOOD: vi.mock at the top level (gets hoisted)
vi.mock('./api');
import { fetchUser } from './api'; // now receives the mock

// GOOD: use vi.doMock for non-hoisted mocking
test('test with specific mock', async () => {
  vi.doMock('./api', () => ({
    fetchUser: vi.fn().mockResolvedValue({ id: 1 }),
  }));
  // Must use dynamic import AFTER doMock
  const { fetchUser } = await import('./api');
  const result = await fetchUser(1);
  expect(result).toEqual({ id: 1 });
});

// Clean up after doMock
afterEach(() => {
  vi.doUnmock('./api');
  vi.resetModules(); // clear module cache
});
```

`vi.doMock` is the escape hatch for when hoisting doesn't work or you need different mocks per test. Always pair with `vi.resetModules()` in cleanup.

This error often appears when jest methods are used outside of test files, or when jest globals aren't available in the execution context.

```typescript
// Error: Cannot read properties of undefined (reading 'fn')
// Cause: using jest.fn() in a file that isn't a test file

// BAD: mock in a shared utility file
// src/utils/test-helpers.ts
export const mockFetch = jest.fn(); // Error if imported outside jest context

// GOOD: use conditional check or move to test file
// src/utils/test-helpers.ts
export function createMockFetch() {
  if (typeof jest === 'undefined') {
    throw new Error('createMockFetch can only be used in test files');
  }
  return jest.fn();
}

// GOOD: keep mocks in test files or __mocks__ directories
// src/__mocks__/api.ts
export const fetchUser = jest.fn();
export const updateUser = jest.fn();

// Also happens when:
// 1. testEnvironment is wrong (node vs jsdom)
// 2. setupFiles imports something that uses jest before it's initialized
// 3. jest.config has incorrect transform settings
```

Check that the file is matched by your `testMatch` or `testRegex` pattern in jest.config. Files outside the test pattern don't get the Jest runtime injected.

By default, the `node` test environment doesn't provide `fetch`. You need Node 18+ or a polyfill.

```typescript
// Error: ReferenceError: fetch is not defined

// Fix 1: Use Node 18+ (fetch is built-in)
// Ensure your node version is 18+

// Fix 2: Add fetch polyfill to setup
// test/setup.ts
import { fetch, Headers, Request, Response } from 'undici';

globalThis.fetch = fetch as any;
globalThis.Headers = Headers as any;
globalThis.Request = Request as any;
globalThis.Response = Response as any;

// Fix 3: Use MSW which provides its own fetch interception
import { setupServer } from 'msw/node';
import { http, HttpResponse } from 'msw';

const server = setupServer(
  http.get('*/api/users', () => HttpResponse.json([]))
);

beforeAll(() => server.listen());
afterEach(() => server.resetHandlers());
afterAll(() => server.close());

// Fix 4: Use jsdom environment (includes fetch)
// @vitest-environment jsdom
// or in config: test.environment = 'jsdom'
```

For API testing, MSW is the best solution because it mocks at the network level, working with any HTTP client (fetch, axios, got, etc.).

Jest can't parse non-JavaScript files. CSS, images, and other assets throw syntax errors unless you configure transforms or module name mappers.

```typescript
// Error: SyntaxError: Unexpected token '.'
// Caused by: import './styles.css' or import logo from './logo.png'

// jest.config.ts
export default {
  moduleNameMapper: {
    // Mock CSS imports
    '\\.(css|less|scss|sass)$': 'identity-obj-proxy',

    // Mock file imports
    '\\.(jpg|jpeg|png|gif|svg|webp|woff|woff2|ttf|eot)$':
      '<rootDir>/test/__mocks__/fileMock.ts',
  },

  // Or use transform for CSS modules
  transform: {
    '^.+\\.tsx?$': 'ts-jest',
    '^.+\\.css$': '<rootDir>/test/transforms/cssTransform.ts',
  },
};
```

```typescript
// test/__mocks__/fileMock.ts
export default 'test-file-stub';

// test/transforms/cssTransform.ts
import type { SyncTransformer } from '@jest/transform';
const transformer: SyncTransformer = {
  process() {
    return { code: 'module.exports = {};' };
  },
};
export default transformer;
```

`identity-obj-proxy` returns the CSS class name as-is, so `styles.button` returns `'button'`. This lets you assert on class names in component tests.

This error occurs when trying to use `vi.spyOn` on a module that re-exports primitives or when the module mock hasn't been set up correctly.

```typescript
// config.ts
export const API_URL = 'https://api.example.com';
export const TIMEOUT = 5000;

// BAD: can't spy on primitive exports
import * as config from './config';
vi.spyOn(config, 'API_URL'); // Error: Cannot spy on a primitive value

// GOOD: mock the module instead
vi.mock('./config', () => ({
  API_URL: 'https://test-api.example.com',
  TIMEOUT: 1000,
}));

// GOOD: for functions, spyOn works fine
import * as utils from './utils';
vi.spyOn(utils, 'formatDate').mockReturnValue('2024-01-01');

// GOOD: use vi.stubEnv for environment variables
vi.stubEnv('API_URL', 'https://test-api.example.com');

// For mocking constants that change per test:
const mockConfig = { API_URL: 'https://test.com' };
vi.mock('./config', () => mockConfig);

test('uses custom URL', () => {
  mockConfig.API_URL = 'https://custom.com';
  // ... test code that reads config.API_URL
});
```

`vi.spyOn` only works on object methods (functions), not on primitive values. For primitive exports, use `vi.mock` to replace the entire module.

Default Jest timeout is 5 seconds. Async tests that take longer silently fail with a timeout error.

```typescript
// Error: thrown: "Exceeded timeout of 5000 ms for a test."

// Fix 1: Increase timeout for specific test
test('slow integration test', async () => {
  const result = await longRunningOperation();
  expect(result).toBeDefined();
}, 30000); // 30 second timeout

// Fix 2: Increase globally
// jest.config.ts
export default {
  testTimeout: 10000, // 10 seconds for all tests
};

// Fix 3: Increase for a describe block
describe('integration tests', () => {
  jest.setTimeout(30000);

  test('test 1', async () => { /* ... */ });
  test('test 2', async () => { /* ... */ });
});

// Common causes of timeout:
// 1. Forgot to await an async operation
// 2. Mock not set up — real API call timing out
// 3. Unresolved promise (missing resolve in manual mock)
// 4. done callback not called in callback-style tests

// Debug: check if a mock is missing
test('should not make real API calls', async () => {
  // If this takes > 1s, you're probably hitting a real API
  const start = Date.now();
  await fetchUser(1);
  expect(Date.now() - start).toBeLessThan(100);
});
```

The jest-dom matchers for Vitest require a specific import path that changed in recent versions.

```bash
# Install
npm install -D @testing-library/jest-dom
```

```typescript
// test/setup.ts

// For @testing-library/jest-dom v6+:
import '@testing-library/jest-dom/vitest';

// For older versions:
import '@testing-library/jest-dom';

// If neither works, extend manually:
import * as matchers from '@testing-library/jest-dom/matchers';
import { expect } from 'vitest';

expect.extend(matchers);
```

```typescript
// vitest.config.ts
export default defineConfig({
  test: {
    setupFiles: ['./test/setup.ts'],
    globals: true,
  },
});

// tsconfig.json — add types for autocompletion
{
  "compilerOptions": {
    "types": ["vitest/globals", "@testing-library/jest-dom"]
  }
}
```

This gives you matchers like `toBeInTheDocument()`, `toHaveTextContent()`, `toBeVisible()`, `toHaveClass()`, etc. These are essential for readable DOM assertions.

Jest uses its own module resolution which can differ from your bundler. This causes 'Cannot find module' errors for files that work fine in your app.

```typescript
// Error: Cannot find module '../components/Button' from 'src/tests/Button.test.tsx'

// jest.config.ts — common fixes
export default {
  // Match TypeScript paths
  moduleNameMapper: {
    '^@/(.*)$': '<rootDir>/src/$1',
  },

  // Set module directories
  moduleDirectories: ['node_modules', 'src'],

  // Resolve file extensions in order
  moduleFileExtensions: ['ts', 'tsx', 'js', 'jsx', 'json'],

  // Root directory
  roots: ['<rootDir>/src'],

  // If using absolute imports like 'components/Button'
  modulePaths: ['<rootDir>/src'],
};

// Debugging: see how Jest resolves modules
// Run: npx jest --showConfig | grep -A 20 moduleNameMapper
// Run: npx jest --verbose --no-cache src/tests/Button.test.tsx
```

The most common cause is mismatched path aliases between `tsconfig.json` and `jest.config.ts`. Tools like `ts-jest/utils` or `jest-module-name-mapper` can auto-sync them.

If you set `environment: 'jsdom'` globally but have server-side code that shouldn't run in a browser context, you'll get errors or incorrect behavior.

```typescript
// Error: window is not defined (in Node environment)
// Or: unexpected behavior because jsdom provides a fake window

// server-utils.ts
export function isServer() {
  return typeof window === 'undefined'; // false in jsdom!
}

// Fix: use environment per-file
// api.test.ts
// @vitest-environment node
import { isServer } from './server-utils';

test('detects server', () => {
  expect(isServer()).toBe(true); // correct in node environment
});

// Or configure patterns in config
export default defineConfig({
  test: {
    environment: 'node', // default to node
    environmentMatchGlobs: [
      ['**/*.dom.test.ts', 'jsdom'],     // DOM tests
      ['**/*.component.test.tsx', 'jsdom'], // React tests
      // Everything else runs in node
    ],
  },
});
```

Default to `node` environment and only use `jsdom` for files that actually need DOM APIs. This prevents subtle bugs where server code behaves differently in jsdom.

When Jest says values are not equal but the diff looks identical, it's usually a serialization issue — the objects differ in non-visible ways.

```typescript
// Common causes:

// 1. Date objects vs strings
expect(result.createdAt).toBe('2024-01-15'); // Date !== string
// Fix: convert to same type
expect(result.createdAt.toISOString()).toContain('2024-01-15');

// 2. Numbers vs strings
expect(result.count).toBe('5'); // number !== string
// Fix: use correct type
expect(result.count).toBe(5);

// 3. Object identity (toBe vs toEqual)
expect({ a: 1 }).toBe({ a: 1 }); // different objects!
// Fix: use toEqual for deep equality
expect({ a: 1 }).toEqual({ a: 1 });

// 4. Symbol properties or non-enumerable properties
const a = { x: 1 };
Object.defineProperty(a, 'hidden', { value: 2, enumerable: false });
expect(a).toEqual({ x: 1 }); // passes, but...
expect(a).toStrictEqual({ x: 1 }); // may fail

// 5. Buffer/ArrayBuffer comparison
expect(Buffer.from('hello')).toEqual(Buffer.from('hello')); // use toEqual

// Debug: log the actual types
console.log(typeof result.createdAt); // 'object' (Date) vs 'string'
console.log(JSON.stringify(result, null, 2)); // see actual structure
```

V8 coverage provider can crash with segfaults in large projects due to memory issues.

```typescript
// vitest.config.ts — fix for coverage crashes
export default defineConfig({
  test: {
    coverage: {
      // Switch to istanbul provider (more stable for large projects)
      provider: 'istanbul',

      // Or keep v8 but limit scope
      provider: 'v8',
      include: ['src/**/*.{ts,tsx}'],
      exclude: [
        'src/**/*.test.{ts,tsx}',
        'src/**/*.stories.{ts,tsx}',
        'src/types/**',
        'node_modules/**',
      ],
    },

    // Increase memory for workers
    pool: 'forks', // forks isolate better than threads
    poolOptions: {
      forks: {
        execArgv: ['--max-old-space-size=4096'],
      },
    },
