The React ecosystem moved from Enzyme to Testing Library. Understanding why helps write better tests.

**Enzyme (legacy):**
```typescript
// Tests implementation details
const wrapper = shallow(<Counter />);
expect(wrapper.state('count')).toBe(0);
wrapper.find('button').simulate('click');
expect(wrapper.state('count')).toBe(1);
// Tests break when you refactor internals, even if behavior is the same
```

**Testing Library (current):**
```typescript
// Tests user behavior
render(<Counter />);
expect(screen.getByText('Count: 0')).toBeInTheDocument();
await userEvent.click(screen.getByRole('button', { name: 'Increment' }));
expect(screen.getByText('Count: 1')).toBeInTheDocument();
// Tests survive refactors — only break when behavior changes
```

**Key philosophy differences:**
- Enzyme: test component internals (state, props, lifecycle)
- Testing Library: test what the user sees and does

**Enzyme can't test:**
- Hooks (useEffect, useState) — only class components
- React 18+ features (Suspense, startTransition)
- Server Components

**Testing Library advantages:**
- Framework-agnostic (React, Vue, Angular, Svelte)
- Encourages accessible markup (queries prefer ARIA roles)
- Tests are resilient to refactoring
- Works with all React versions including 18+

If you're starting a new project, there's no reason to use Enzyme. For existing projects, migrate file-by-file — both can coexist temporarily.

In watch mode, Vitest only re-runs tests affected by changed files. This is fast but can miss failures caused by shared state or cross-file dependencies.

```bash
