Timestamps, random IDs, and dynamic content make snapshots fail every run. You must stabilize non-deterministic values.

```typescript
// BAD: snapshot contains current timestamp
test('creates record', () => {
  const record = createRecord();
  expect(record).toMatchSnapshot();
  // Snapshot includes: createdAt: '2024-03-28T10:30:45.123Z'
  // Fails tomorrow because timestamp changed
});

// GOOD: use property matchers
test('creates record', () => {
  const record = createRecord();
  expect(record).toMatchSnapshot({
    id: expect.any(String),
    createdAt: expect.any(Date),
    updatedAt: expect.any(Date),
  });
});

// GOOD: freeze time
vi.useFakeTimers();
vi.setSystemTime(new Date('2024-01-01T00:00:00Z'));

// GOOD: mock random values
vi.spyOn(Math, 'random').mockReturnValue(0.5);
vi.spyOn(crypto, 'randomUUID').mockReturnValue('test-uuid-1234');
```

Property matchers tell the snapshot serializer to only check the type, not the value. This is the cleanest solution for fields that change between runs.

Using `getBy` for elements that appear after an async operation returns null or throws immediately instead of waiting for the element.

```typescript
// BAD: getBy doesn't wait for async rendering
test('loads user data', async () => {
  render(<UserProfile id={1} />);
  expect(screen.getByText('Alice')).toBeInTheDocument();
  // Throws: Unable to find an element with the text: Alice
  // Because data hasn't loaded yet
});

// GOOD: findBy waits (with timeout)
test('loads user data', async () => {
  render(<UserProfile id={1} />);
  expect(await screen.findByText('Alice')).toBeInTheDocument();
  // Waits up to 1000ms (default) for element to appear
});

// GOOD: waitFor for multiple assertions
test('loads user data', async () => {
  render(<UserProfile id={1} />);
  await waitFor(() => {
    expect(screen.getByText('Alice')).toBeInTheDocument();
    expect(screen.getByText('alice@test.com')).toBeInTheDocument();
  });
});

// Query types:
// getBy  — sync, throws if not found (use for elements that exist now)
// findBy — async, waits and retries (use for elements appearing later)
// queryBy — sync, returns null if not found (use for asserting absence)
expect(screen.queryByText('Error')).not.toBeInTheDocument();
```

This warning means something in your test created a persistent connection or timer that wasn't cleaned up.

```bash
# Error: Jest has detected the following open handle(s) potentially keeping Jest from exiting
# Find the handles:
npx jest --detectOpenHandles

# Common causes:
# 1. Database connection not closed
# 2. HTTP server still listening
# 3. setInterval not cleared
# 4. Event listener not removed
```

```typescript
// Fix 1: close database connections
afterAll(async () => {
  await prisma.$disconnect();
  await pool.end();
});

// Fix 2: close HTTP servers
let server: ReturnType<typeof app.listen>;
beforeAll(() => {
  server = app.listen(0); // random port
});
afterAll(() => {
  server.close();
});

// Fix 3: clear intervals
const interval = setInterval(poll, 1000);
afterEach(() => clearInterval(interval));

// Fix 4: force exit as last resort (not recommended)
// jest.config.ts
export default {
  forceExit: true, // kills process after tests complete
  // Better: fix the open handles
};
```

`--forceExit` masks the real problem. Use `--detectOpenHandles` to find and fix the leak. In Vitest, the equivalent issue is less common because workers are more isolated.

This occurs when a mock accidentally calls itself, or when circular dependencies cause infinite mock resolution.

```typescript
// BAD: mock calls the original which calls the mock
vi.mock('./api', async (importOriginal) => {
  const original = await importOriginal<typeof import('./api')>();
  return {
    fetchUser: vi.fn(async (id) => {
      // This calls the mock itself, not the original!
      return original.fetchUser(id);
    }),
  };
});

// GOOD: capture original before returning mock
let originalFetchUser: typeof import('./api').fetchUser;

vi.mock('./api', async (importOriginal) => {
  const original = await importOriginal<typeof import('./api')>();
  originalFetchUser = original.fetchUser;
  return {
    fetchUser: vi.fn().mockImplementation((id) => {
      // Only call original when explicitly needed
      return { id, name: 'Mock User' };
    }),
  };
});

// GOOD: don't call original at all in mock
vi.mock('./api', () => ({
  fetchUser: vi.fn().mockResolvedValue({ id: 1, name: 'Mock User' }),
}));
```

If you need both real and mock behavior, use `vi.spyOn` which preserves the original by default, and you can override per-test with `.mockImplementation()`.

